var tafsirData_39 = {
  1: {
    "The revelation of this Book": "This Quran that you are receiving is not a human invention or the words of any created being. It is a divine revelation—a Book sent down from the heavens to guide humanity. The word 'revelation' emphasizes that this scripture came from above, not from earthly sources.",
    "is from Allah": "The source of this Book is Allah Himself, the Creator of all things. This establishes the ultimate authority of the Quran. When something comes from Allah, it carries the highest level of truth and cannot be questioned in its authenticity.",
    "the Almighty": "Allah is Al-Aziz—the One who possesses absolute power and might. No one can overpower Him or prevent His will from being executed. This attribute reassures believers that the One sending this guidance has complete control over all affairs.",
    "All-Wise": "Allah is Al-Hakeem—the One whose every action, command, and decree is based on perfect wisdom. Nothing in His revelation is random or without purpose. Every verse, every ruling, and every story in the Quran serves a wise purpose, even if we may not immediately understand it."
  },
  2: {
    "Indeed, We have sent down the Book to you ˹O Prophet˺ in truth": "Allah confirms that He sent this Quran to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) with absolute truth. The Quran contains no falsehood, no contradictions, and no errors. Everything in it—its stories, laws, promises, and warnings—is completely true. This was important to establish because the disbelievers accused the Prophet of making it up.",
    "so worship Allah ˹alone˺": "Because this Book is true and from Allah, the natural response is to worship Allah alone. Worship here means all acts of devotion, obedience, prayer, and submission. The command is direct and clear: your worship should be directed only to Allah, not to any idol, person, or created thing.",
    "being sincerely devoted to Him": "Sincerity (Ikhlas) is the soul of worship. It means doing acts of worship purely for Allah's sake, not to show off, not to gain people's praise, and not for any worldly benefit. A prayer performed to impress others has no value with Allah. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Allah does not accept any deed except that which is done sincerely for His sake.' (Sunan An-Nasa'i)"
  },
  3: {
    "Indeed, sincere devotion is due ˹only˺ to Allah": "Pure, sincere worship belongs exclusively to Allah. This is a fundamental principle of Islam (Tawheed). No one else deserves any portion of our worship—not angels, not prophets, not saints, not any created being. Allah alone created us, sustains us, and will judge us, so He alone deserves our devotion.",
    "As for those who take other lords besides Him": "This refers to the polytheists who worshipped idols, saints, or other beings alongside Allah. They assigned divine qualities to created things, seeking their help and directing worship to them. This includes anyone who gives ultimate loyalty, love, or obedience to something other than Allah.",
    "˹saying,˺ \"We worship them only so they may bring us closer to Allah\"": "This was the excuse of the Arab polytheists. They claimed they knew Allah was the Supreme Creator, but they worshipped idols as intermediaries, believing these could intercede for them with Allah. They thought they needed a 'middleman' to reach God. This logic is rejected because Allah is closer to us than our jugular vein (Quran 50:16) and needs no intermediaries. A person doesn't need someone to introduce them to a king who already knows them intimately.",
    "surely Allah will judge between all regarding what they differed about": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will settle all disputes about religion and belief. Those who associated partners with Him will face the consequences of their false claims. The truth will be made absolutely clear, and no excuses will be accepted.",
    "Allah certainly does not guide whoever persists in lying and disbelief": "Those who deliberately lie about Allah—claiming He has partners, children, or that their false worship is acceptable—and who stubbornly persist in disbelief will not receive Allah's guidance. This is a divine principle: guidance is given to those who sincerely seek truth, not to those who knowingly reject it and insist on falsehood."
  },
  4: {
    "Had it been Allah's Will to have offspring": "This verse addresses those who falsely claim that Allah has children—whether the Arab polytheists who said angels were Allah's daughters, or others who attributed a son to God. Allah hypothetically addresses this claim: IF He had wanted offspring (which He does not), He would not need any biological process.",
    "He could have chosen whatever He willed of His creation": "Allah is not limited or dependent on anyone. If He wanted, He could simply choose and designate any of His creation. But the point is that Allah is far above needing offspring. Humans have children because of biological need, desire for legacy, or need for help in old age. Allah has none of these limitations.",
    "Glory be to Him!": "This is a declaration of Allah's perfection and transcendence (Subhanahu). He is free from all imperfections, including the false attributes people assign to Him. Having offspring implies need and limitation, and Allah is absolutely free from all needs.",
    "He is Allah—the One, the Supreme": "Allah is Al-Wahid (the One)—unique in His essence, attributes, and actions. There is nothing like Him. He is Al-Qahhar (the Supreme, the Irresistible)—He has absolute dominion over all creation. Everything submits to His will, whether willingly or unwillingly. This combination of names emphasizes that Allah stands alone in His majesty and power."
  },
  5: {
    "He created the heavens and the earth for a purpose": "The creation of the universe is not random or meaningless. Allah created everything with truth, wisdom, and purpose. The heavens and earth serve as signs of Allah's existence, as a test for humanity, and as a stage for human life. This counters any belief that existence is accidental or purposeless.",
    "He wraps the night around the day, and wraps the day around the night": "This beautiful description shows how night gradually covers day and day gradually covers night, like a turban being wrapped around a head. This continuous cycle happens smoothly across the spherical earth. The word 'yukawwir' (wraps/coils) is remarkably accurate—it suggests a round object being covered, which aligns with the earth's spherical shape. This daily transition is a sign of Allah's precise control over creation.",
    "And He has subjected the sun and the moon, each orbiting for an appointed term": "The sun and moon are not independent powers worthy of worship (as some ancient peoples believed). They are created things, subjected to Allah's command, following exact paths He determined. Each celestial body moves in its orbit until an appointed time—the Day of Judgment when the current cosmic order will end. Scientists today confirm the precise mathematical orbits of these bodies.",
    "He is truly the Almighty, Most Forgiving": "Despite His overwhelming power (Al-Aziz), Allah is also Al-Ghaffar (the Most Forgiving, the Repeatedly Forgiving). He forgives sins again and again for those who repent. This combination of might and mercy encourages believers: we should fear His power but also hope in His forgiveness."
  },
  6: {
    "He created you ˹all˺ from a single soul": "All of humanity originated from one person—Adam (peace be upon him). This establishes human unity and equality. No race or nation is inherently superior because everyone shares the same origin. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said in his farewell sermon: 'All mankind is from Adam, and Adam was created from dust. No Arab has superiority over a non-Arab except by piety.'",
    "then from it He made its mate": "From Adam, Allah created his wife Hawwa (Eve). This shows that the human pair was created to complement each other. Marriage and family are part of Allah's design from the very beginning of human existence.",
    "And He produced for you four pairs of cattle": "Allah mentions His blessing of creating eight types of cattle in pairs (male and female): sheep, goats, cows, and camels. These animals provide humans with food, milk, leather, wool, and transportation. This is a reminder of Allah's care for human needs.",
    "He creates you in the wombs of your mothers ˹in stages˺, one development after another": "Human development in the womb happens in distinct stages—from a drop of fluid, to a clinging clot, to a lump of flesh, then bones, then flesh covering bones, and finally a complete human being. This miraculous process, described in the Quran 1400 years ago, has been confirmed by modern embryology. It demonstrates Allah's creative power and knowledge.",
    "in three layers of darkness": "The developing baby is protected within three layers: the amniotic membrane, the uterine wall, and the abdominal wall of the mother. This triple protection ensures the baby's safety and proper development. Some scholars also interpret this as the darkness of the abdomen, the darkness of the womb, and the darkness of the placental membranes.",
    "That is Allah—your Lord! All authority belongs to Him": "After presenting these amazing signs of creation, Allah reminds us that He alone is our Lord (Rabb)—the Creator, Sustainer, and Owner of everything. All dominion and sovereignty belong to Him exclusively.",
    "There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him": "This is the declaration of Tawheed (monotheism). Since Allah alone creates, sustains, and controls everything, He alone deserves worship. No created being shares these abilities, so no created being deserves worship.",
    "How can you then be turned away?": "This is a rhetorical question expressing amazement: After seeing all these clear signs of Allah's creative power and lordship, how can anyone turn away from worshipping Him alone? How can anyone be so misguided as to worship something other than the Creator?"
  },
  7: {
    "If you disbelieve, then ˹know that˺ Allah is truly not in need of you": "Allah does not need human worship or faith. He is Al-Ghani (the Self-Sufficient). Our belief or disbelief does not benefit or harm Allah in any way. A person who chooses disbelief only harms themselves. This is like someone refusing to eat healthy food—the food's value doesn't decrease, but the person suffers.",
    "nor does He approve of disbelief from His servants": "Even though Allah doesn't need our faith, He does not want disbelief for us because He is merciful and wants good for His servants. Disbelief leads to punishment, and Allah, out of His mercy, doesn't want that for people. He commands belief for our own benefit, not His.",
    "But if you become grateful ˹through faith˺, He will appreciate that from you": "When you believe and show gratitude to Allah, He appreciates it and rewards you abundantly. Gratitude here includes faith, worship, and using Allah's blessings in ways that please Him. Allah multiplies the reward for gratitude, even though He gains nothing from it.",
    "No soul burdened with sin will bear the burden of another": "This is a fundamental principle of divine justice. On the Day of Judgment, no one will be punished for someone else's sins. Each person is responsible only for their own actions. A parent won't bear the sins of their child, and a child won't bear the sins of their parent. This encourages personal responsibility and offers hope—your fate is in your own hands.",
    "Then to your Lord is your return": "Everyone will return to Allah after death for final judgment. There is no escape from this meeting. Whether one believes or disbelieves, rich or poor, powerful or weak—all will stand before Allah.",
    "and He will inform you of what you used to do": "On that Day, Allah will present a complete record of every person's deeds—every good and bad action, even those forgotten or hidden. Nothing escapes Allah's knowledge. This should motivate us to be conscious of our actions at all times.",
    "He certainly knows best what is ˹hidden˺ in the heart": "Allah's knowledge extends beyond outward actions to the innermost secrets of the heart—our intentions, hidden desires, secret jealousies, and concealed faith or hypocrisy. Nothing is hidden from Him. This reminds us to purify not just our actions but our hearts as well."
  },
  8: {
    "When one is touched with hardship, they cry out to their Lord, turning to Him ˹alone˺": "Human nature reveals itself in times of crisis. When a person faces serious hardship—illness, danger, loss, or any calamity—they instinctively turn to Allah alone. In those desperate moments, they forget all the false gods and focus entirely on the Creator. This shows that deep down, the human soul (fitrah) recognizes Allah as the only true helper.",
    "But as soon as He showers them with blessings from Him, they ˹totally˺ forget the One they had cried to earlier": "Once the hardship is removed and blessings come, many people forget their prayers and promises to Allah. They become busy with their comfort and pleasures, as if the crisis never happened. This short memory and ingratitude is a spiritual disease that blinds people to Allah's continuous favors.",
    "and set up equals to Allah to mislead ˹others˺ from His Way": "Even worse, some people after being saved return to associating partners with Allah and even lead others astray. They attribute their success to luck, their own abilities, or false gods, ignoring the One who truly rescued them. By doing this, they not only destroy themselves but also mislead others.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Enjoy your disbelief for a little while!\"": "Allah instructs the Prophet to deliver this stern warning: Go ahead and enjoy your temporary pleasures and false beliefs. This worldly life is short. The enjoyment of disbelief is brief compared to eternity.",
    "You will certainly be one of the inmates of the Fire": "The destination of those who persist in ingratitude and disbelief is the Hellfire. This is stated with certainty to shake the disbeliever out of their heedlessness. The pleasures of this world are not worth eternal punishment."
  },
  9: {
    "˹Are they better˺ or those who worship ˹their Lord˺ devoutly in the hours of the night": "Allah presents a powerful contrast. Are the ungrateful disbelievers equal to those who spend their nights in worship? The righteous believer sacrifices sleep to stand before Allah when others are resting. The night prayer (Tahajjud) is particularly beloved to Allah because it requires sincerity—no one sees you except Allah.",
    "prostrating and standing": "The believer alternates between prostration (sujood) and standing (qiyam) in prayer. These are the physical postures of submission and devotion. The night is described as being filled with these acts of worship.",
    "fearing the Hereafter": "The devout worshipper is motivated by healthy fear of the Day of Judgment—fear of standing before Allah, fear of accountability, fear of punishment for sins. This fear keeps them obedient and away from sins.",
    "and hoping for the mercy of their Lord": "Along with fear, the believer has hope in Allah's mercy, forgiveness, and reward. A balanced faith combines both fear and hope—fear prevents arrogance and sin, while hope prevents despair. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'None of you should die except while having good expectations of Allah.' (Sahih Muslim)",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Are those who know equal to those who do not know?\"": "This rhetorical question emphasizes the obvious answer: No, they are not equal! Those who know Allah, know the truth of revelation, and act upon their knowledge are completely different from those who are ignorant and heedless. Knowledge here means beneficial knowledge that leads to good action.",
    "None will be mindful ˹of this˺ except people of reason": "Only those with sound intellect and understanding will truly reflect on these truths and benefit from them. 'People of reason' (Ulul Albab) are those who use their minds to ponder Allah's signs and act accordingly. They are not swayed by desires or blind following."
  },
  10: {
    "Say ˹O Prophet, that Allah says˺, \"O My servants who believe!\"": "Allah lovingly addresses the believers as 'My servants'—a title of honor. Being a servant of Allah is the highest status a human can achieve. This address creates a direct connection between Allah and the believers.",
    "Be mindful of your Lord": "Taqwa (mindfulness/consciousness of Allah) is commanded. It means being aware of Allah at all times, doing what He commands, and avoiding what He forbids. Taqwa is the foundation of all good deeds and the protection against sins.",
    "Those who do good in this world will have a good reward": "Those who perform righteous deeds in this worldly life will receive a good reward—both in this world (peace of mind, barakah, good reputation) and in the Hereafter (Paradise and Allah's pleasure). Good actions are never wasted with Allah.",
    "And Allah's earth is spacious": "If you cannot practice your religion freely in one place due to persecution, migrate to another place where you can worship Allah. Allah's earth is vast. This was particularly relevant when the early Muslims faced persecution in Mecca and some migrated to Abyssinia and later to Madinah. It remains relevant for Muslims facing religious oppression anywhere.",
    "Only those who endure patiently will be given their reward without limit": "Patience (Sabr) has unlimited rewards. While other good deeds have specified rewards (some multiplied by 10, some by 700), the reward for patience has no calculation or limit—it is given abundantly beyond measure. This is because patience is difficult and encompasses many situations: patience in worship, patience in avoiding sins, and patience during hardships."
  },
  11: {
    "Say, \"I am commanded to worship Allah\"": "The Prophet (peace be upon him) is told to publicly announce that he has received a divine command to worship Allah. This worship is not optional or self-invented—it is a command from the Creator.",
    "being sincerely devoted to Him ˹alone˺": "Again, sincerity (Ikhlas) is emphasized. The Prophet's worship is purely for Allah, with no mixed intentions. He is setting the example for all believers. If the Prophet himself is commanded to have sincere devotion, how much more important is it for everyone else?"
  },
  12: {
    "And I am commanded to be the first of those who submit ˹to His Will˺": "The Prophet (peace be upon him) was commanded to be the leader in submission to Allah among his community. He was to be the foremost example of a Muslim—one who submits completely to Allah. A true leader leads by example, and the Prophet was the first to practice what he preached."
  },
  13: {
    "Say, \"I truly fear—if I were to disobey my Lord—the torment of a tremendous Day\"": "Even the Prophet, who was guaranteed Paradise, expressed fear of disobeying Allah. This teaches profound humility. If the best of creation fears Allah's punishment, ordinary people should fear it even more. The 'tremendous Day' is the Day of Judgment—a day so severe that its torment would be unbearable. This fear is not weakness; it is wisdom and awareness of Allah's greatness."
  },
  14: {
    "Say, \"It is ˹only˺ Allah that I worship\"": "The Prophet declares with emphasis: Allah alone is the object of my worship. The sentence structure in Arabic puts 'Allah' first for emphasis—Allah, and no one else.",
    "being sincere in my devotion to Him": "For the third time in these verses, sincerity is mentioned. This repetition shows its critical importance. All worship must be done with pure intention, solely seeking Allah's pleasure. Worship mixed with showing off, seeking praise, or worldly motives is rejected."
  },
  15: {
    "Worship then whatever ˹gods˺ you want instead of Him": "This is a stern statement of disassociation. If the disbelievers refuse to worship Allah alone, they are left to their false worship—but they will bear the consequences. It is a form of warning disguised as permission.",
    "Say, \"The ˹true˺ losers are those who will lose themselves and their families on Judgment Day\"": "The real bankruptcy is not financial—it is spiritual. On the Day of Judgment, the disbelievers will lose everything: their own souls will be condemned to Hell, and they will be separated from their loved ones forever. They will have no family to comfort them and no salvation for themselves. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described the truly bankrupt person as one who comes on the Day of Judgment with good deeds but has wronged others, so their good deeds are taken away until they have nothing left. (Sahih Muslim)",
    "That is indeed the clearest loss": "This is emphasized as the most obvious, undeniable loss. Worldly losses can be recovered, but losing one's eternal soul and being condemned to Hell forever is a loss from which there is no recovery."
  },
  16: {
    "They will have layers of fire above and below them": "The punishment of the disbelievers in Hell is comprehensive—fire will surround them from every direction. Sheets of fire will be above them like canopies, and fire will be beneath them as well. There will be no escape, no relief, and no direction to turn to for comfort.",
    "That is what Allah warns His servants with": "This terrifying description is a warning from Allah to His servants. The purpose is not to terrorize but to awaken—to make people realize the seriousness of disbelief and the reality of the punishment that awaits. A warning from a loving Creator is a mercy.",
    "So fear Me, O My servants!": "Allah concludes with a direct, compassionate call: 'O My servants, fear Me!' He still calls them 'My servants,' showing that His door remains open for those who turn back to Him. The fear of Allah leads to obedience, and obedience leads to salvation."
  },
  17: {
    "And those who shun the worship of false gods": "Taghut refers to anything worshipped besides Allah, including idols, Satan, tyrannical leaders who demand obedience in disobedience to Allah, and one's own desires when they lead away from Allah's path. The righteous servants actively avoid and reject all forms of false worship.",
    "turning to Allah ˹alone˺": "They don't just abandon falsehood—they turn wholeheartedly to Allah. Inabah (turning to Allah) means returning to Him with repentance, love, and obedience. They replace false worship with true worship.",
    "will have good news": "For these people, there is glad tidings (Bushra). Good news awaits them in this life and the next—news of Allah's pleasure, forgiveness, and Paradise. Angels will give them good news at the time of death (Quran 41:30), and they will receive good news on the Day of Judgment.",
    "So give good news to My servants ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah instructs His Prophet to be a bearer of good news to the believers. Islam is not only about warnings; it is also about hope, joy, and glad tidings for those who believe and do good."
  },
  18: {
    "those who listen to what is said": "These servants have open ears and minds. They listen attentively to various statements, arguments, and teachings. They are not closed-minded or arrogant.",
    "and follow the best of it": "After listening, they use their intelligence and follow what is best—the truth, the guidance, the higher path. When given options, they choose the better one. For example, when Islam gives the option between retaliation and forgiveness, they may choose forgiveness. They seek excellence in their practice of religion.",
    "These are the ones ˹rightly˺ guided by Allah": "Such people have received true guidance from Allah. Their ability to recognize and follow truth is itself a blessing from Allah. Guidance is not random—it comes to those who sincerely seek it.",
    "and these are ˹truly˺ the people of reason": "They are the people of intellect (Ulul Albab). True intelligence is not just academic knowledge but the wisdom to recognize truth and act upon it. A truly intelligent person uses their mind to reach Allah, not to argue against Him."
  },
  19: {
    "What about those against whom the decree of torment has been justified?": "Some people, due to their persistent rejection of truth and insistence on disbelief, have had Allah's decree of punishment become binding upon them. This happens when someone completely closes their heart to guidance.",
    "Is it you ˹O Prophet˺ who will then save those bound for the Fire?": "This is a rhetorical question addressed to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). Even the Prophet, with all his concern for people's salvation, cannot save someone who is destined for Hell due to their own choices. Guidance is from Allah alone. The Prophet can only convey the message; he cannot force hearts to believe. This also comforted the Prophet, reminding him not to grieve excessively over those who refused to believe."
  },
  20: {
    "But those mindful of their Lord": "In contrast to those destined for punishment, there are those who lived with Taqwa—consciousness of Allah. They feared His displeasure and worked to earn His pleasure.",
    "will have ˹elevated˺ mansions, built one above the other": "Their reward is lofty chambers in Paradise (Ghuraf)—not just single rooms but mansions upon mansions, multi-storied and elevated. The higher the chamber, the greater the honor. These descriptions give us a glimpse of the unimaginable luxury awaiting the believers.",
    "under which rivers flow": "Rivers flow beneath these mansions—rivers of water, milk, honey, and wine (pure, non-intoxicating). This imagery represents ultimate comfort, beauty, and serenity. The believers will have everything they desire.",
    "˹That is˺ the promise of Allah": "This is not a human promise that might be broken. It is Allah's promise (Wa'dAllah), and Allah never fails to fulfill His promises.",
    "˹And˺ Allah never fails in ˹His˺ promise": "Emphasis is given: Allah does not break His word. What He has promised of reward for the believers and punishment for the disbelievers will certainly come to pass. This should fill believers with hope and motivate them to strive for these rewards."
  },
  21: {
    "Do you not see that Allah sends down rain from the sky": "Allah directs our attention to a phenomenon we witness regularly but often take for granted. Rain comes from the sky—a mercy from Allah that sustains all life on earth.",
    "channelling it through streams in the earth": "The rainwater doesn't just stay on the surface. Allah causes it to penetrate the earth, forming underground springs, wells, and aquifers. This stored water then becomes available when needed. It's an amazing system of water management designed by the Creator.",
    "then produces with it crops of various colours": "From this water, Allah brings forth vegetation of stunning diversity—different colors, types, and varieties of crops. Look at a garden or farm: greens, reds, yellows, purples—all coming from the same water and soil. This variety is a sign of Allah's creative power.",
    "then they dry up and you see them wither": "But this lush vegetation doesn't last. Eventually, the crops mature, begin to age, and turn yellow. What was once vibrant and full of life starts to wilt and fade. This is the natural cycle.",
    "and then He reduces them to chaff": "Finally, the plants become dry, broken debris (Hutam)—scattered pieces good only for animal feed or to be blown away. The once beautiful crops become worthless remnants.",
    "Surely in this is a reminder for people of reason": "This entire cycle is a parable for worldly life. Human life, like plants, has its seasons—youth, maturity, old age, and death. Worldly possessions and pleasures also follow this pattern—they are temporary, fading, and eventually turn to nothing. The wise person sees this natural cycle and understands not to attach their heart to temporary things but to invest in the eternal Hereafter."
  },
  22: {
    "Can ˹the misguided be like˺ those whose hearts Allah has opened to Islam": "Sharh al-Sadr (expansion of the chest) is a beautiful concept. When Allah guides someone, He expands their heart to receive faith. Islam enters easily, and obedience becomes joyful rather than burdensome. The heart that was once tight with anxiety becomes spacious with peace. The Prophet (peace be upon him) was asked about this expansion, and he said it means light being cast into the heart, and a sign of it is turning toward the eternal home and away from the deceptive world. (Ibn Kathir)",
    "so they are enlightened by their Lord": "Such a person walks in light (Nur) from Allah. They see truth clearly, make wise decisions, and navigate life's challenges with divine guidance. This light illuminates their path in this world and will literally light their way on the Day of Judgment.",
    "So woe to those whose hearts are hardened at the remembrance of Allah!": "In stark contrast are those whose hearts become harder when they hear Allah's name or His verses. Instead of softening and submitting, their hearts become like stone—or even harder. The Quran says stones are better because at least some rivers flow from them (Quran 2:74). These people's hearts reject guidance completely.",
    "It is they who are clearly astray": "Their misguidance is obvious and undeniable. They have strayed far from the path of truth and are lost in their arrogance and heedlessness. Their hardened hearts have led them to clear error."
  },
  23: {
    "˹It is˺ Allah ˹Who˺ has sent down the best message": "The Quran is described as 'Ahsan al-Hadith'—the best speech, the most beautiful discourse. No human speech can compare to Allah's words. It is the best in its meanings, its style, its guidance, and its effect on hearts.",
    "a Book of perfect consistency": "The Quran is 'Mutashabih' in the sense that its verses resemble each other in beauty and perfection. There are no contradictions, no errors, and no inferior portions. Every part confirms and supports other parts. Despite being revealed over 23 years in various circumstances, it maintains perfect harmony.",
    "and repeated lessons": "The Quran is 'Mathani'—its lessons, stories, and themes are repeated throughout for emphasis and reinforcement. Stories of prophets are told multiple times from different angles. Warnings and promises are reiterated. This repetition serves to strengthen understanding and memory.",
    "which causes the skin ˹and hearts˺ of those who fear their Lord to tremble": "When believers who truly fear Allah hear the Quran, their skin shivers. This is a physical reaction to the power and majesty of Allah's words—trembling from awareness of His greatness, His warnings, and His promises. It's like standing before something awesome and overwhelming.",
    "then their skin and hearts soften at the mention of ˹the mercy of˺ Allah": "But this fear doesn't remain as terror. When verses of mercy, forgiveness, and hope are heard, the believer's skin and heart soften with comfort and hope. The Quran produces this beautiful balance—fear that prevents arrogance and hope that prevents despair. The companions of the Prophet would experience this when listening to the Quran.",
    "That is the guidance of Allah, through which He guides whoever He wills": "This effect of the Quran—the trembling and softening—is a sign of Allah's guidance. Not everyone experiences this. It is Allah's gift to those He chooses to guide. Guidance comes from Him alone.",
    "But whoever Allah leaves to stray will be left with no guide": "Those whom Allah does not guide due to their own rejection and arrogance will find no one else to guide them. No scholar, no teacher, no system can guide someone if Allah has withdrawn His guidance from them. This happens as a consequence of their own choices."
  },
  24: {
    "Are those who will only have their ˹bare˺ faces to shield themselves from the awful torment on Judgment Day ˹better than those in Paradise˺?": "This is a vivid and terrifying image. On the Day of Judgment, the wrongdoers will be brought with their hands tied. They will have nothing to protect themselves except their faces—the most honored part of the body, usually the last thing a person would use as a shield. When fire comes at them, they can only turn their faces toward it helplessly. Compare this to the believers who will be in gardens of bliss—how can these two groups be equal?",
    "It will ˹then˺ be said to the wrongdoers: \"Reap what you sowed!\"": "The wrongdoers will be told to taste the consequences of their own actions. They earned this punishment through their choices in the worldly life. There is no injustice—they are simply receiving the results of what they themselves acquired. This is a universal principle: actions have consequences, and the Hereafter is when the full consequences become manifest."
  },
  25: {
    "Those before them ˹also˺ rejected ˹the truth˺": "The pattern of rejection is not new. Previous nations—the people of Nuh, Ad, Thamud, the people of Lut, and others—all rejected the truth when it came to them. They denied their messengers just as the Quraysh were denying Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).",
    "then the torment came upon them from where they least expected": "Allah's punishment came suddenly and from unexpected directions. The people of Lut didn't expect stones from the sky. Pharaoh didn't expect to drown in the same sea he had crossed safely many times. The wrongdoers of Makkah are being warned: don't think you're safe just because you don't see immediate punishment. It can come from where you least anticipate."
  },
  26: {
    "So Allah made them taste humiliation in this worldly life": "Their punishment wasn't delayed until the Hereafter. They tasted disgrace (Khizy) in this world itself—destruction, defeat, loss of power, and being made examples for later generations. Their names became synonymous with divine punishment.",
    "but far worse is the punishment of the Hereafter": "As terrible as their worldly punishment was, it was nothing compared to what awaits them in the Hereafter. The punishment of Hell is greater in intensity, severity, and duration—it is eternal.",
    "if only they knew": "If only they had knowledge and understanding! If they truly comprehended what awaits disbelievers in the Hereafter, they would never have rejected the truth. But their ignorance, arrogance, and desire for worldly pleasures blinded them from this reality."
  },
  27: {
    "We have certainly set forth every ˹kind of˺ lesson for people in this Quran": "Allah has included in the Quran every type of example, parable, and lesson that humanity needs. Stories of past nations, descriptions of Paradise and Hell, parables from nature, logical arguments—everything necessary for guidance is there. The Quran is comprehensive and complete.",
    "so perhaps they will be mindful": "The purpose of these varied examples is to make people reflect and remember. Different types of examples appeal to different types of people and different aspects of the human mind. Some are moved by stories, others by logical arguments, others by descriptions of consequences. Allah, in His wisdom, provides all of these so that people may become mindful (Yatadhakarun) and take heed."
  },
  28: {
    "˹It is˺ a Quran ˹revealed˺ in Arabic": "Allah chose to reveal the Quran in Arabic—a rich, precise, and eloquent language. This was the language of the Prophet and his people, so they could understand it directly. Arabic was also a language capable of expressing the profound meanings of divine revelation with unmatched precision.",
    "without any crookedness": "The Quran has no defects, contradictions, deviations, or confusion. It is completely straight (Ghayr dhi iwaj)—its meanings are clear, its guidance is direct, and its message is consistent. There is nothing crooked or unclear about it when approached with sincerity.",
    "so perhaps they will be conscious ˹of Allah˺": "The ultimate goal of the Quran's perfection and clarity is Taqwa—consciousness of Allah. When people read or hear this flawless Book in clear language, they are meant to develop awareness of Allah, fear of His punishment, hope in His mercy, and obedience to His commands. The Quran is not just for intellectual appreciation but for transformation of the heart and life."
  },
  29: {
    "Allah sets forth the parable of a slave owned by several quarrelsome masters": "Allah presents a powerful comparison to illustrate the difference between polytheism and monotheism. Imagine a slave who is owned by multiple masters, and these masters constantly argue and disagree with each other. One master orders him to go east, another orders him to go west. One demands one thing, another demands the opposite. This slave is in constant confusion, stress, and anxiety—he can never please all his masters, and he is pulled in different directions without peace.",
    "and a slave owned by only one master": "Now imagine another slave who belongs to just one master. He knows exactly what is expected of him, his duties are clear, and he can focus all his efforts on pleasing one person. His life is peaceful, organized, and purposeful.",
    "Are they equal in condition?": "This is the rhetorical question Allah poses. Obviously, they are not equal! The slave with one master is in a far better condition. This is exactly like the difference between a polytheist—who tries to please multiple gods, saints, or desires—and a monotheist who worships Allah alone. The believer has clarity, peace, and direction. The polytheist is confused, torn between conflicting loyalties, and never at rest.",
    "Praise be to Allah!": "All praise belongs to Allah who has guided us to Tawheed (monotheism) and saved us from the confusion of polytheism. This is also a declaration that Allah alone deserves praise, not the false gods.",
    "In fact, most of them do not know": "Despite how obvious this truth is, most people do not understand or reflect upon it. They remain in their ignorance, worshipping multiple false gods or following multiple contradictory desires, when the path of worshipping One God is clearly superior."
  },
  30: {
    "You ˹O Prophet˺ will certainly die": "Even the best of creation, Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), will die. This verse was a reminder to the Prophet himself and a powerful message to everyone else: no one is exempt from death. When the Prophet passed away, some companions were in denial until Abu Bakr recited: 'Muhammad is no more than a messenger, and other messengers have passed away before him' (Quran 3:144). If the Prophet must die, then certainly everyone else must too.",
    "and they will die too": "The disbelievers, the enemies of Islam, the powerful, the weak—all will die. Death is the great equalizer. Those who oppose the truth thinking they will escape accountability are gravely mistaken. Death will come to them just as it comes to everyone."
  },
  31: {
    "Then on the Day of Judgment you will ˹all settle your˺ dispute before your Lord": "Death is not the end. After death comes resurrection, and all disputes will be settled before Allah. The arguments between believers and disbelievers, the oppressed and oppressors, the truthful and the liars—all will be brought before Allah for final judgment. No disagreement will remain unresolved. The truth will be made absolutely clear, and justice will be served perfectly."
  },
  32: {
    "Who then does more wrong than those who lie about Allah": "There is no greater injustice than fabricating lies about Allah—claiming He has partners, children, or that He commanded things He never commanded. Those who invent false beliefs about Allah and attribute them to Him commit the worst form of wrongdoing.",
    "and reject the truth after it has reached them?": "Even worse is when the truth comes clearly to someone, and they deliberately reject it. These are not people who never heard the message—the truth reached them through clear signs, prophets, and revelation, yet they stubbornly refused to accept it. This willful rejection is a grave sin.",
    "Is Hell not a ˹fitting˺ home for the disbelievers?": "This rhetorical question confirms that Hell is the appropriate destination for such people. They chose to lie about Allah and reject His truth, so their fitting abode is the Fire. It is not injustice—it is the natural consequence of their choices."
  },
  33: {
    "And the one who has brought the truth": "This refers primarily to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), who brought the truth from Allah—the Quran and the complete message of Islam. It also applies to all prophets and anyone who conveys truth.",
    "and those who embrace it": "These are the believers who accept the truth when it comes to them. They don't reject it out of arrogance or stubbornness. They recognize truth and submit to it.",
    "it is they who are the righteous": "These people—the bringers and accepters of truth—are the Muttaqoon (the righteous, the God-conscious). They have achieved true piety because they aligned themselves with truth and lived by it. This is the essence of Taqwa: recognizing truth and following it."
  },
  34: {
    "They will have whatever they desire with their Lord": "The reward for the righteous is limitless. In Paradise, they will have anything they wish for—pleasures beyond imagination, reunions with loved ones, eternal youth, and above all, the pleasure of Allah. Whatever their hearts desire will be granted. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that in Paradise, there is what no eye has seen, no ear has heard, and no human heart has imagined. (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "That is the reward of the good-doers": "This is the recompense for the Muhsinoon—those who worship Allah as if they see Him, knowing that even if they don't see Him, He sees them. Excellence in worship and conduct leads to excellence in reward."
  },
  35: {
    "As such, Allah will absolve them of ˹even˺ the worst of what they did": "Allah, in His mercy, will wipe away even the worst sins of the righteous believers. Their past mistakes, their moments of weakness—all will be forgiven and erased. This is the power of sincere faith and repentance. A person should never despair of Allah's mercy.",
    "and reward them according to the best of what they used to do": "Not only will their worst deeds be forgiven, but they will be rewarded based on their best deeds. Allah looks at the best of what they did and rewards them accordingly. This is incredible generosity—the bad is erased, and the good is multiplied. This should motivate every believer to strive for excellence while having hope in Allah's forgiveness."
  },
  36: {
    "Is Allah not sufficient for His servant?": "This is a powerful rhetorical question affirming that Allah is absolutely sufficient for whoever relies on Him. The Prophet (peace be upon him) was threatened by the pagans who said their idols would harm him, but Allah reassured him: I am enough for you. When a person has Allah, they need nothing else. This applies to all believers who trust in Allah—He is sufficient to protect, provide, and guide.",
    "Yet they threaten you with other ˹powerless˺ gods besides Him!": "The pagans tried to frighten the Prophet by claiming their idols would curse him or bring misfortune upon him. But how can powerless idols—who cannot help themselves—harm anyone? These threats were empty because the idols had no power whatsoever.",
    "Whoever Allah leaves to stray will be left with no guide": "Those whom Allah does not guide, due to their own rejection and arrogance, cannot find guidance anywhere else. No false god, no human leader, no system can guide them if Allah has withdrawn His guidance. This is a warning about the consequences of persistent disbelief."
  },
  37: {
    "And whoever Allah guides, none can lead astray": "The flip side is equally true: when Allah guides someone, no force in existence can mislead them. Not Satan, not evil companions, not temptations—nothing can derail a person whom Allah has chosen to guide. This is reassuring for believers: hold onto Allah's guidance, and no one can take it from you.",
    "Is Allah not Almighty, capable of punishment?": "Allah is Al-Aziz (the Almighty) with complete power, and He is Dhul-Intiqam (capable of punishment/retribution). He can punish those who oppose Him and His messengers whenever He wills. The disbelievers should not feel safe just because punishment is delayed—Allah has full power to exact justice."
  },
  38: {
    "If you ask them ˹O Prophet˺ who created the heavens and the earth, they will certainly say, \"Allah!\"": "Even the polytheists of Makkah acknowledged that Allah was the Creator of the universe. They didn't deny His existence or His role as Creator. Their problem was that despite knowing this, they still worshipped other beings alongside Him.",
    "Ask ˹them˺, \"Consider then whatever ˹idols˺ you invoke besides Allah: if it was Allah's Will to harm me, could they undo that harm?\"": "This is a logical challenge. If Allah decides to afflict someone with harm, can any of these idols remove it? The obvious answer is no. These idols have no power to override Allah's decree.",
    "Or if He willed ˹some˺ mercy for me, could they withhold His mercy?": "Similarly, if Allah decides to bestow mercy on someone, can these idols prevent it? Again, no. They have no power to stop Allah's blessings. So what is the point of worshipping beings that can neither harm nor benefit anyone independently?",
    "Say, \"Allah is sufficient for me\"": "This is the declaration of true trust in Allah: Hasbiyallah—Allah is enough for me. When a person truly believes this, they are freed from fear of any created thing. The Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) said these words when thrown into the fire, and Allah made the fire cool and safe for him.",
    "In Him ˹alone˺ the faithful put their trust": "Those who truly trust in Allah (Al-Mutawakkiloon) rely on Him alone. Tawakkul (trust in Allah) means doing your best while leaving the results to Allah, knowing He will take care of your affairs better than anyone else could."
  },
  39: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O my people! Persist in your ways, for I ˹too˺ will persist in mine\"": "The Prophet is instructed to issue this firm statement to his people. It's a warning disguised as a challenge: You continue doing what you're doing, and I will continue on my path. This is not giving up on them but rather a final declaration after delivering the message repeatedly. Each party will see the consequences of their choices.",
    "You will soon come to know": "The truth will become clear soon. Whether in this world or the Hereafter, the results will reveal who was on the right path. This is a confident statement—the Prophet knows the truth is on his side and time will prove it."
  },
  40: {
    "who will be visited by a humiliating torment ˹in this life˺": "The disbelievers will face humiliating punishment in this worldly life. This could come in the form of defeat in battle, loss of status, or other forms of disgrace. The polytheists of Makkah experienced this at the Battle of Badr and other encounters.",
    "and overwhelmed by an everlasting punishment ˹in the next˺": "Beyond the worldly punishment, they will face eternal punishment in the Hereafter. The word 'Muqeem' (everlasting/permanent) emphasizes that this punishment will never end. The temporary enjoyments of disbelief lead to permanent suffering."
  },
  41: {
    "Surely We have revealed to you the Book ˹O Prophet˺ with the truth for humanity": "The Quran was revealed with truth, containing truth, and for the benefit of all humanity—not just one tribe, nation, or time period. It is universal guidance for all people until the Day of Judgment.",
    "So whoever chooses to be guided, it is for their own good": "The benefit of accepting guidance returns to the person themselves. Allah doesn't need anyone's faith—when you believe and follow guidance, you are helping yourself, securing your own salvation and success.",
    "And whoever chooses to stray, it is only to their own loss": "Similarly, whoever rejects guidance only harms themselves. They are not harming Allah or the Prophet—they are destroying their own souls and their own future.",
    "You are not a keeper over them": "The Prophet's duty is to convey the message, not to force people to believe. He is not responsible for their choices. He is not their guardian or controller. Allah alone has power over hearts. This also served to comfort the Prophet who was grieving over those who refused to believe."
  },
  42: {
    "˹It is˺ Allah ˹Who˺ calls back the souls ˹of people˺ upon their death": "Allah takes the souls at the time of death. Death is not random—it is Allah who causes it to happen at the precise moment He has decreed. No one dies before their time, and no one can delay it.",
    "as well as ˹the souls˺ of the living during their sleep": "Allah also takes souls during sleep, though in a different way than death. Sleep is called 'the minor death' because the soul partially leaves the body. This is why we often don't know what happens around us while sleeping and why the Prophet taught us to say a supplication before sleeping and upon waking, thanking Allah for returning our souls.",
    "Then He keeps those for whom He has ordained death": "Some souls taken during sleep are not returned—these are the people whose time of death has come. They simply don't wake up. This happens to people every day around the world.",
    "and releases the others until ˹their˺ appointed time": "The other souls are sent back to their bodies to continue living until their appointed time of death arrives. Every time we wake up, it is because Allah chose to return our soul to us.",
    "Surely in this are signs for people who reflect": "This daily cycle of sleep and waking is a powerful sign of Allah's control over life and death. Every night we experience a 'mini-death' and every morning we experience 'resurrection.' Those who reflect on this will understand Allah's power and the reality of the final resurrection."
  },
  43: {
    "Or have they taken others besides Allah as intercessors?": "The polytheists claimed their idols would intercede for them with Allah. They believed worshipping these beings would earn them special favor and access to Allah.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"˹Would they do so,˺ even though those ˹idols˺ have neither authority nor intelligence?\"": "The Prophet is told to challenge their logic: How can these idols intercede when they possess nothing and understand nothing? They have no power to benefit or harm anyone, and they are not even conscious beings. An intercessor needs to have standing and ability—these idols have neither. How foolish to rely on such entities!"
  },
  44: {
    "Say, \"All intercession belongs to Allah ˹alone˺\"": "Intercession is entirely in Allah's control. No one can intercede except with His permission, and He only permits intercession for those He approves of. The Prophet (peace be upon him) will intercede on the Day of Judgment, but only after Allah grants him permission and only for those Allah allows. Intercession cannot be demanded from anyone besides Allah.",
    "To Him belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth": "Allah owns everything—no one else has independent authority. The idols own nothing, so how can they intercede?",
    "Then to Him you will ˹all˺ be returned": "Everyone will return to Allah for judgment. Whether one worshipped idols or worshipped Allah alone, all will stand before Him. This should motivate people to ensure they are on the right path before that Day arrives."
  },
  45: {
    "Yet when Allah alone is mentioned, the hearts of those who disbelieve in the Hereafter are filled with disgust": "This is a telling sign of a diseased heart: when Allah alone is mentioned—without any partners—the disbelievers feel discomfort, aversion, and disgust. The pure message of Tawheed bothers them because it threatens their false beliefs and desires.",
    "But as soon as those ˹gods˺ other than Him are mentioned, they are filled with joy": "However, when their idols and false gods are mentioned, they become happy and excited. This reveals where their true attachment lies. A healthy heart should be the opposite—finding joy in the mention of Allah and discomfort when false gods are glorified. This is a diagnostic test for one's faith."
  },
  46: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O Allah—Originator of the heavens and the earth\"": "The Prophet is taught to call upon Allah with His beautiful names. 'Fatir' means the One who originated and created something unprecedented—He created the heavens and earth from nothing, without any prior model.",
    "Knower of the seen and unseen!": "Allah knows everything—what is apparent and what is hidden, what has happened and what will happen, what is in hearts and what is displayed openly. Nothing is hidden from Him.",
    "You will judge between Your servants regarding their differences": "All the disputes about religion, truth, and guidance will be settled by Allah. He knows who was right and who was wrong, who was sincere and who was hypocritical. His judgment will be final and perfect."
  },
  47: {
    "Even if the wrongdoers were to possess everything in the world twice over, they would certainly offer it to ransom themselves from the horrible punishment on Judgment Day": "On that Day, the punishment will be so severe that wrongdoers would gladly give everything imaginable to escape it—not just all the wealth on earth, but double that amount. But it will not be accepted. No ransom will be taken. This shows how terrifying the punishment will be and how worthless worldly wealth becomes at that moment.",
    "for they will see from Allah what they had never expected": "They will encounter punishments and realities they never imagined. In this world, they may have thought lightly of Allah's warnings or denied the Hereafter entirely. But they will face a reality far worse than anything they could have conceived. The horrors of Hell will shock them completely."
  },
  48: {
    "And the evil ˹consequences˺ of their deeds will unfold before them": "All the bad deeds they committed in the world—which they may have forgotten or dismissed—will be presented before them. Every sin, every act of injustice, every moment of arrogance will be laid bare. There will be no hiding or denying.",
    "and they will be overwhelmed by what they used to ridicule": "The punishment they mocked will surround them. They used to laugh at warnings about Hell, make fun of believers, and ridicule the concept of resurrection. Now that very thing they mocked will engulf them, and there will be no escape."
  },
  49: {
    "When one is touched with hardship, they cry out to Us ˹alone˺": "This pattern is repeated in the Quran because it's so common: when humans face serious difficulty—illness, poverty, danger—they turn sincerely to Allah alone, abandoning all other attachments. In desperation, the natural human instinct (fitrah) recognizes the true source of help.",
    "Then when We shower Our blessings upon them, they say, \"I have been granted all this only because of ˹my˺ knowledge\"": "Once the hardship is removed and blessings come, the same person forgets Allah and attributes success to their own intelligence, skills, hard work, or connections. They say, 'I earned this myself.' This was the attitude of Qarun (Korah), who said about his wealth: 'I have been given it only because of knowledge I possess' (Quran 28:78).",
    "Not at all! It is ˹no more than˺ a test": "Allah corrects this arrogant thinking: No! Your blessings are not proof of your worthiness or intelligence—they are a test. Will you be grateful or arrogant? Will you recognize Allah or become prideful? Blessings can be a trial just as much as hardships.",
    "But most of them do not know": "Most people fail to understand this reality. They don't realize that wealth, health, and success are tests from Allah, not signs of His approval of their behavior."
  },
  50: {
    "The same had already been said by those ˹destroyed˺ before them": "Previous nations made the same arrogant claims. They attributed their success to themselves and denied Allah's role. Qarun, Pharaoh, the people of Ad and Thamud—all had similar attitudes.",
    "but their ˹worldly˺ gains were of no benefit to them": "When Allah's punishment came, all their wealth, power, and achievements could not save them. Their possessions did not protect them from destruction. This is a warning: don't be deceived by temporary success."
  },
  51: {
    "So the evil ˹consequences˺ of their deeds overtook them": "Their arrogance and ingratitude eventually caught up with them. The punishment for their sins befell them, and they could not escape.",
    "And the wrongdoers among these ˹pagans˺ will be overtaken by the evil ˹consequences˺ of their deeds": "The same fate awaits the wrongdoers of today—specifically the pagans of Makkah who behaved like previous nations. History repeats itself for those who don't learn from it.",
    "And they will have no escape": "They cannot outrun Allah's decree. They cannot hide from His punishment. They will not be able to frustrate or weaken Allah's plan in any way. When punishment comes, there is no refuge."
  },
  52: {
    "Do they not know that Allah gives abundant or limited provisions to whoever He wills?": "Wealth and poverty are not signs of Allah's love or anger. Allah expands provision for some and restricts it for others based on His wisdom, not based on who deserves it more. A righteous person may be poor, and a wicked person may be rich. This is all part of Allah's test and plan.",
    "Surely in this are signs for people who believe": "Believers understand this truth. They don't measure their worth by their wealth, and they don't assume the wealthy are favored by Allah. They see the distribution of provision as a sign of Allah's wisdom and sovereignty, not as a measure of spiritual status. This understanding brings contentment and prevents both arrogance in wealth and despair in poverty."
  },
  53: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet, that Allah says,˺ \"O My servants who have exceeded the limits against their souls!\"": "This is one of the most hopeful verses in the entire Quran. Allah addresses those who have committed many sins and transgressed greatly. Notice He still calls them 'My servants'—a term of honor and belonging, even though they have sinned. The sins are described as being 'against their souls' because every sin harms the sinner first and foremost. When we disobey Allah, we are not harming Him—He is beyond being harmed—we are damaging ourselves.",
    "Do not lose hope in Allah's mercy": "No matter how many sins one has committed, no matter how severe they are, one must never despair of Allah's mercy. Despair itself is a sin because it suggests that Allah's mercy is limited. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'If you were to commit sins until your sins reached the sky, then you repented, Allah would accept your repentance.' (Ibn Majah). Even a person who has committed the worst sins imaginable should never give up hope.",
    "for Allah certainly forgives all sins": "This is an absolute statement—Allah forgives ALL sins for those who sincerely repent. Murder, adultery, theft, lying, shirk (if one repents before death)—everything can be forgiven. The scholars explain that this applies to those who repent; otherwise, shirk without repentance is not forgiven (Quran 4:48). But with sincere repentance, even the worst crimes are wiped away.",
    "He is indeed the All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Allah's names Al-Ghafoor (the All-Forgiving) and Ar-Raheem (the Most Merciful) are mentioned to reinforce the message. Forgiveness is part of Allah's nature. He loves to forgive and is delighted when His servant turns back to Him. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Allah is more pleased with the repentance of His servant than a man who loses his camel in the desert and then suddenly finds it.' (Muslim)"
  },
  54: {
    "Turn to your Lord ˹in repentance˺": "Inabah means turning to Allah with sincere repentance—not just saying words, but genuinely returning to Him with the heart. It includes regretting past sins, stopping the sin immediately, and resolving not to return to it.",
    "and ˹fully˺ submit to Him": "Along with repentance comes complete submission (Islam) to Allah. This means surrendering your will, obeying His commands, and accepting His decree. True repentance leads to obedience.",
    "before the punishment reaches you": "There is urgency in this call. Repentance must happen before it's too late. This could refer to death, which comes without warning, or to punishments in this world, or to the Day of Judgment.",
    "˹for˺ then you will not be helped": "Once punishment arrives, there will be no help, no rescue, and no second chance. The time for repentance will have passed. This creates urgency—don't delay turning back to Allah."
  },
  55: {
    "Follow ˹the Quran,˺ the best of what has been revealed to you from your Lord": "The Quran is described as 'the best of what has been revealed'—it is the finest guidance, the most perfect book. Following it means reading it, understanding it, and living by its teachings. This is the path to salvation.",
    "before the punishment takes you by surprise while you are unaware": "Punishment can come suddenly and unexpectedly. Death can come at any moment—while eating, sleeping, or going about daily activities. The wise person prepares before that moment arrives, not after."
  },
  56: {
    "so that no ˹sinful˺ soul will say ˹on Judgment Day˺, 'Woe to me for neglecting ˹my duties towards˺ Allah'": "On that Day, the sinful soul will cry out in deep regret: 'Ya Hasrata!' (What grief! What loss!). They will realize they wasted their lives neglecting what Allah commanded, ignoring His rights upon them, and failing to prepare for this Day.",
    "while ridiculing ˹the truth˺": "Adding to their regret is the memory of how they used to mock the truth, make fun of believers, and ridicule religious matters. What seemed funny in the world becomes a source of unbearable shame on that Day."
  },
  57: {
    "Or ˹a soul will˺ say, 'If only Allah had guided me, I would have certainly been one of the righteous'": "Another excuse people will try: blaming Allah for not guiding them. They will claim it wasn't their fault—if Allah had guided them, they would have been righteous. This is a false excuse because Allah sent messengers, revealed books, and made the truth clear. Guidance was offered, but they rejected it."
  },
  58: {
    "Or say, upon seeing the torment, 'If only I had a second chance, I would have been one of the good-doers'": "When they actually see the punishment, they will desperately wish for another chance. 'Send me back! Let me try again! I'll be good this time!' But this world was their chance. There are no do-overs after death. The Quran tells us that even if they were sent back, they would return to the same sins (Quran 6:28)."
  },
  59: {
    "Not at all!": "Allah rejects all these excuses with a firm 'Bala!' (Yes indeed! / Not so!). The excuses don't hold.",
    "My revelations had already come to you": "The truth was presented to them clearly. Allah's signs in creation, His revealed Books, His messengers—all came to them. They had every opportunity to believe.",
    "but you rejected them": "Despite having access to the truth, they chose to deny it. This was a conscious choice, not ignorance.",
    "acted arrogantly": "Their rejection was rooted in arrogance (istikbar). They were too proud to submit to Allah, too proud to follow a prophet, too proud to change their ways. Arrogance is one of the most dangerous spiritual diseases.",
    "and were one of the disbelievers": "Their fate was sealed by their own choices. They ended up among the disbelievers not because Allah forced them, but because they chose that path."
  },
  60: {
    "On the Day of Judgment you will see those who lied about Allah with their faces gloomy": "On that Day, the liars—those who attributed false things to Allah, claimed He had partners or children, or invented lies about His religion—will be visibly marked. Their faces will be blackened with gloom, darkness, and humiliation. Just as they darkened their souls with lies, their faces will display that darkness for all to see.",
    "Is Hell not a ˹fitting˺ home for the arrogant?": "This rhetorical question confirms that Hell is the appropriate destination for the arrogant. Arrogance (kibr) is what led them to lie about Allah and reject the truth. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'No one who has an atom's weight of arrogance in their heart will enter Paradise.' (Muslim)"
  },
  61: {
    "And Allah will deliver those who were mindful ˹of Him˺ to their place of ˹ultimate˺ triumph": "In contrast, those who had Taqwa (consciousness of Allah) will be saved and brought to success (Mafazah). This word implies achievement, victory, and attaining what one hoped for. They will reach the ultimate goal—Paradise and Allah's pleasure.",
    "No evil will touch them": "They will be completely protected from any harm or punishment. The terrors of that Day, the punishment of Hell, all forms of evil—none will reach them.",
    "nor will they grieve": "They will have no grief or sadness. All the sorrows of worldly life will be forgotten, and they will have nothing to grieve about in the Hereafter. This is complete happiness and security."
  },
  62: {
    "Allah is the Creator of all things": "Everything that exists—the heavens, the earth, angels, humans, animals, plants, atoms, galaxies—all were created by Allah. Nothing exists independently of Him. This includes all the false gods people worship; they too are created things and thus cannot be true gods.",
    "and He is the Maintainer of everything": "Not only did Allah create everything, but He also maintains, manages, and controls everything. He is the Wakeel (Guardian, Disposer of Affairs) over all creation. Every affair is in His hands. This should inspire complete trust (tawakkul) in Him."
  },
  63: {
    "To Him belong the keys ˹of the treasuries˺ of the heavens and the earth": "Allah holds the keys to all treasures and provisions in the heavens and earth. Rain, sustenance, guidance, mercy, knowledge—access to all blessings is with Him. He opens and closes these treasures as He wills. When He gives, none can withhold; when He withholds, none can give.",
    "As for those who rejected the signs of Allah, it is they who will be the ˹true˺ losers": "Those who denied Allah's signs—in creation and in revelation—are the real losers. They lost the opportunity to access Allah's treasures of guidance and mercy. Their loss is not temporary or partial; it is complete and eternal."
  },
  64: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Are you urging me to worship ˹anyone˺ other than Allah, O ignorant ones?\"": "The pagans of Makkah tried to persuade the Prophet (peace be upon him) to compromise—perhaps worship their gods sometimes, or show respect to their idols. The Prophet is commanded to respond with shock and disbelief: How can you ask me to worship anything besides Allah? He calls them 'ignorant' (jahiloon) because anyone who suggests worshipping other than Allah demonstrates profound ignorance of who Allah truly is."
  },
  65: {
    "It has already been revealed to you—and to those ˹prophets˺ before you": "This message is not new. Every prophet received the same revelation about the gravity of shirk. From Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all), the message was consistent.",
    "that if you associate others ˹with Allah˺, your deeds will certainly be void": "Shirk (associating partners with Allah) nullifies all good deeds. Even if a person prayed, fasted, gave charity, and did many good works—if they committed shirk, all of it would be wasted. This is like building a beautiful house on a foundation of sand; it all collapses. Tawheed (monotheism) is the foundation upon which all good deeds must be built.",
    "and you will truly be one of the losers": "Even prophets, if they hypothetically committed shirk (which they are protected from), would be among the losers. This shows that no one is exempt from this rule. The message is clear: shirk leads to total loss, regardless of who commits it."
  },
  66: {
    "Rather, worship Allah ˹alone˺": "Instead of the shirk they suggest, the command is clear and emphatic: worship Allah alone. The word 'bal' (rather) shows a strong rejection of their suggestion and a redirection to the truth.",
    "and be one of the grateful": "Gratitude (shukr) accompanies proper worship. When you worship Allah alone, you naturally become grateful because you recognize that all blessings come from Him. Gratitude is expressed through the heart (feeling thankful), the tongue (saying thanks), and the limbs (using blessings in obedience to Allah)."
  },
  67: {
    "They have not shown Allah His proper reverence": "The polytheists failed to appreciate Allah's true majesty and greatness. By assigning partners to Him, they diminished His status in their minds. They did not give Him the respect, honor, and worship He deserves.",
    "when on the Day of Judgment the ˹whole˺ earth will be in His Grip": "To illustrate Allah's true power, the Quran describes the Day of Judgment: the entire earth—with all its mountains, oceans, and continents—will be in Allah's grip like something tiny and insignificant. This is beyond human imagination.",
    "and the heavens will be rolled up in His Right Hand": "The vast heavens—with all their stars, galaxies, and cosmic structures—will be rolled up like a scroll in Allah's right hand. This imagery shows Allah's absolute power over creation. What seems immense and permanent to us is nothing before Allah.",
    "Glorified and Exalted is He above what they associate ˹with Him˺!": "After this description of Allah's majesty, He is declared far above and free from the partners they ascribe to Him. How can anyone compare anything to a Being of such magnitude?"
  },
  68: {
    "The Trumpet will be blown": "The angel Israfil will blow the Trumpet (Sur)—a horn whose sound will signal the end of this world as we know it. This is the first blowing.",
    "and all those in the heavens and all those on the earth will fall dead, except those Allah wills ˹to spare˺": "At this first blast, every living being in existence—humans, jinn, angels (most of them)—will die. Only those whom Allah chooses to exempt will survive. Scholars differ on who these exceptions are, but they may include certain angels or martyrs.",
    "Then it will be blown again": "After a period of time, the Trumpet will be blown a second time.",
    "and they will rise up at once, looking on ˹in anticipation˺": "At this second blast, all the dead will be resurrected. They will rise from their graves, standing and looking around in amazement and anticipation, waiting to see what will happen next. The resurrection will be instantaneous—one moment dead, the next standing alive."
  },
  69: {
    "The earth will shine with the light of its Lord": "On that Day, a special earth will be illuminated by the light of Allah. This is not sunlight or any created light—it is divine light that will illuminate the scene of judgment. This shows the direct manifestation of Allah's presence for judgment.",
    "the record ˹of deeds˺ will be laid ˹open˺": "The books containing every person's deeds will be placed before them. Every action, word, and thought has been recorded by the angels, and now the records will be opened for examination. Nothing will be missing or hidden.",
    "the prophets and the witnesses will be brought forward": "The prophets will be present to testify about their nations—confirming that they delivered the message. The witnesses may include the angels who recorded deeds, the righteous who witnessed events, and the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) who will be a witness over all nations.",
    "and judgment will be passed on all with fairness": "Every person will be judged with perfect justice (bil-haqq). There will be no favoritism, no bribery, no false testimony that succeeds, and no manipulation of the system. Allah's judgment is absolute truth and fairness.",
    "None will be wronged": "Not a single soul will be treated unjustly. No one will be punished for what they didn't do, and no one will be deprived of reward they deserved. This is the ultimate court of justice."
  },
  70: {
    "Every soul will be paid in full for its deeds": "Complete compensation will be given. Good deeds will be rewarded fully (and even multiplied), and bad deeds will be recompensed exactly as deserved. No deed, however small, will be overlooked.",
    "for Allah knows best what they have done": "Allah's knowledge is perfect. He knows not just the external actions, but the intentions behind them, the circumstances, and the hidden aspects. His judgment is based on complete knowledge, unlike any human court which relies on limited evidence."
  },
  71: {
    "Those who disbelieved will be driven to Hell in ˹successive˺ groups": "The disbelievers will be herded toward Hell in groups (zumar)—not led gently, but driven like cattle. This is humiliating for those who were arrogant in the world. They will be grouped perhaps by nation, by type of sin, or by era.",
    "When they arrive there, its gates will be opened": "Hell has gates that will be opened upon their arrival. Unlike Paradise (as we'll see), Hell's gates are closed until they arrive—then they swing open to receive them. This adds to the terror.",
    "and its keepers will ask them: \"Did messengers not come to you from among yourselves\"": "The angels guarding Hell will question them—not to learn something new, but to establish their guilt and remove any excuse. 'Didn't messengers come to you?'",
    "\"reciting to you the revelations of your Lord and warning you of the coming of this Day of yours?\"": "The messengers delivered Allah's message clearly—they recited His revelations and specifically warned about this Day of Judgment. So no one can claim ignorance.",
    "The disbelievers will cry, \"Yes ˹indeed˺!\"": "They will have to admit: Yes, messengers came. Yes, we were warned. There is no denying it now.",
    "But the decree of torment has come to pass against the disbelievers": "They will acknowledge that the word of punishment has been fulfilled against the disbelievers—they are among that group, and there is no escape now."
  },
  72: {
    "It will be said to them, \"Enter the gates of Hell, to stay there forever\"": "The final command is given: Enter Hell permanently. There will be no exit, no parole, no end to the punishment. The word 'khalideen' (forever) emphasizes the eternal nature of their torment.",
    "What an evil home for the arrogant!": "Hell is described as the worst possible dwelling, and it is specifically linked to arrogance (takabbur). Their arrogance prevented them from accepting the truth and submitting to Allah, so Hell became their fitting abode."
  },
  73: {
    "And those who were mindful of their Lord will be led to Paradise in ˹successive˺ groups": "The believers are also taken in groups, but the word 'seeqa' here carries a different tone—they are escorted honorably, like guests of honor being led to a celebration. They are grouped perhaps by virtue, by closeness to Allah, or by era.",
    "When they arrive at its ˹already˺ open gates": "Notice the beautiful difference: unlike Hell whose gates open only when the disbelievers arrive, Paradise's gates are ALREADY open, waiting to welcome them. This shows eagerness to receive the believers.",
    "its keepers will say, \"Peace be upon you!\"": "The angels of Paradise greet them with 'Salamun Alaykum'—peace be upon you. What a contrast to the harsh questioning the disbelievers received! The believers are welcomed with the greeting of peace.",
    "You have done well": "The angels acknowledge their good deeds and righteous lives. 'Tibtum' means you have been pure, good, and wholesome. Their lives were pleasing to Allah.",
    "so come in, to stay forever": "They are invited to enter Paradise and remain there eternally. Unlike worldly pleasures that end, this bliss is permanent. They will never be asked to leave, never fear eviction, never worry about their stay ending."
  },
  74: {
    "The righteous will say, \"Praise be to Allah Who has fulfilled His promise to us\"": "Upon entering Paradise, the believers will praise Allah. They will acknowledge that Allah kept His promise—everything He told them through the messengers and scriptures has come true. Their faith is vindicated, and gratitude overflows.",
    "and made us inherit the ˹everlasting˺ land": "They inherit the land of Paradise as their permanent home. Just as people inherit property to own and live in, the believers inherit Paradise. It becomes theirs by Allah's grace.",
    "to settle in Paradise wherever we please": "They have complete freedom within Paradise—they can settle wherever they wish. There are no restrictions, no borders, no areas off-limits. They roam freely in eternal bliss.",
    "How excellent is the reward of those who work ˹righteousness˺!": "This is an exclamation of appreciation for the reward. All the effort, patience, and sacrifice in the worldly life was worth it. The reward is excellent, perfect, and beyond expectation. This should motivate every believer to work hard for this reward."
  },
  75: {
    "You will see the angels all around the Throne": "The Surah concludes with this magnificent scene: angels surrounding Allah's Throne in countless rows, circling it in devotion and worship. The Throne (Arsh) is the greatest of Allah's creations, and the angels honor it by surrounding it.",
    "glorifying the praises of their Lord": "The angels engage in continuous glorification of Allah—saying 'Subhanallah' (Glory be to Allah) combined with 'Alhamdulillah' (Praise be to Allah). They declare His perfection and praise His attributes. This is the primary activity of the angels.",
    "for judgment will have been passed on all with fairness": "By this point, all judgment has been completed with perfect justice. Everyone has received what they deserved. The matter is concluded, and the decree is final.",
    "And it will be said, \"Praise be to Allah—Lord of all worlds!\"": "The Surah ends as Surah Al-Fatiha begins: 'Alhamdulillahi Rabbil Alameen'—All praise belongs to Allah, the Lord of all worlds. This declaration will be made by the angels, the believers, and all of creation—acknowledging that Allah's judgment was perfect, His promise was true, and He alone deserves all praise. Everything returns to praising Allah. This is the fitting conclusion to a Surah that began by declaring revelation is from Allah and ends with all creation praising Him."
  }
};